nandini roy the clayman institute for gender research skip to main content standford university the clayman institute for gender research the clayman institute for gender research home programs news strategic focus events about research fellowships library media center gender news no news found events no events found you are here home people nandini roy nandini roy ph d candidate department of sociology clayman institute graduate dissertation fellow 2011 12 nandini roy sociology is a doctoral candidate in the department of sociology at stanford university her dissertation research focuses on urban communities and social movements and examines the identity based roots of collective action more specifically she looks at how movement identities like gender and race impact the social networks formed by non profit organizations in san francisco and goes on to examine how these network structures then interact with specific neighborhood demographics to impact levels of collective action experienced by different social movements across the city through her dissertation work roy aims to demonstrate how critically important identities are to social movement formation and show how much impact movement identity can have on movement efficacy donate make a donation social links facebook twitter youtube scribd contact serra house 589 capistrano way stanford ca 94305 8640 map 650 723 1994 gender email stanford edu
